PHISHING EMAIL SAMPLE ANALYSIS – SAMPLE 2

Subject:
Amazon Invoice Payment Confirmation

Sender Email:
billing@amazon-support.net

Greeting:
Dear Customer,


EMAIL MESSAGE

Thank you for your recent purchase from Amazon.

Your order has been successfully processed and an
invoice has been generated for the amount of $489.99.

If you did not authorize this purchase, please review
the invoice immediately by clicking the link below.

View Invoice:
http://amazon-billing-verification.com/invoice

Failure to review the invoice within 24 hours may
result in the charge being processed permanently.

Thank you for shopping with us.

Amazon Billing Department


PHISHING INDICATORS IDENTIFIED

1. Suspicious Sender Domain
The sender email "billing@amazon-support.net" is not
an official Amazon domain. Legitimate Amazon emails
normally come from domains such as @amazon.com.

2. Generic Greeting
The message begins with "Dear Customer" instead of
addressing the user by their real name.

3. Urgency and Fear Tactic
The email creates pressure by suggesting a large
payment has been made and must be reviewed quickly.

4. Suspicious Link
The URL "http://amazon-billing-verification.com"
is not an official Amazon website and may lead to a
malicious page designed to steal login credentials.

5. Unexpected Invoice
Users are often targeted with fake invoices to make
them panic and click malicious links.


EMAIL CLASSIFICATION
Type: Phishing Email
Risk Level: HIGH


ANALYSIS SUMMARY

This phishing email impersonates Amazon and attempts
to trick users into clicking a fake invoice link.
The attacker uses a payment scare tactic to make the
user believe an unauthorized purchase has occurred.

If the user clicks the link and logs in, their Amazon
credentials may be captured by the attacker.

Users should verify sender domains and access their
Amazon account only through the official website.
